aspace_helpers.title: test new ASpace plugin for component-level aspace2alma

comments.body: The plugin is installed.

Another currently-installed plugin, `user_defined_in_basic`, is configured to override the User Defined Fields section needed for archivists to use the new plugin. I'm currently checking in with stakeholders to make sure we can change the config to move `boolean_1` to the Basic Information section without breaking anything.

We can safely move boolean_1 to Basic Information and leave the User Defined Section hidden, based on the current config for `user_defined_in_basic` that Blake sent me:

```
AppConfig[:user_defined_in_basic] = {
  "accessions" => ["date_1", "text_1", "text_2", "text_3", "boolean_1", "boolean_2", "boolean_3", "date_2", "string_1", "string_2", "string_3",  "string_4", "real_1", "real_2", "enum_2"],
  "digital_objects" => [],
  "resources" => [],
  "hide_user_defined_section" => true
}
```
So we're only using the user-defined fields in the Accessions module to begin with, which should make enabling boolean_1 in the Resources module uncontroversial. 

Waiting for ASpace-ops to confirm.

comments.body: Question: This currently generates `.rspec`, `spec/rails_helper.rb`, and `spec/spec_helper.rb`, but the original rails-template commit also adds `spec/support/system_specs.rb` and `spec/system/root_spec.rb`. Is there an RSpec command for generating `spec/support` files, or is this something to add/copy over manually?

@taylor-yamashita Yes, `spec/support` is our local stuff, doesn't come with rspec, so we'll want to bring that over manually. It's in its own commit on that project, https://github.com/pulibrary/rails-template/pull/13/commits/694da5b14f139ac816bf6a98b1dfb95c88239368. Probably the `spec/system/root_spec.rb` is just so there's something that CI can run. It's probably still nice to have that, if we comment it as like an example that should be changed or removed, so that someone could check CI for their new project.

comments.body:
a comment from a while back on the iiif slack:

mat
  [6 months ago](https://iiif.slack.com/archives/C18FHBKAQ/p1666359105940259)
Hey all -- At Northwestern, we’re in the process of moving from Presentation 2.x to 3.0 for our image focused objects, and I’m trying to collect institutional cases of similar moves. Is anyone aware of documented upgrades? I’m mainly concerned with how and/or if Manifests continued to be published at the same URI or if institutions choose to publish v2 and v3 at separate URIs to maintain a past record. (edited) 




8 replies


stephenwf
  [6 months ago](https://iiif.slack.com/archives/C18FHBKAQ/p1666359493243419?thread_ts=1666359105.940259&cid=C18FHBKAQ)
Wellcome did a migration using redirects for existing manifests:
Original (p2)
https://wellcomelibrary.org/iiif/b18035723/manifest
Above redirects to (p2):
https://iiif.wellcomecollection.org/presentation/v2/b18035723
And then the new canonical (p3):
https://iiif.wellcomecollection.org/presentation/v3/b18035723
I'm not sure if they do content negotiation (
[@tomcrane](https://iiif.slack.com/team/U0AQK3TNF)
?) (edited) 


tomcrane
  [6 months ago](https://iiif.slack.com/archives/C18FHBKAQ/p1666359626904269?thread_ts=1666359105.940259&cid=C18FHBKAQ)
Yeah, publish 2 and 3 on new URLs, redirect old 2 to new 2.
Make a canonical path which accepts conneg but also publish explicit version URLs as above.
https://iiif.wellcomecollection.org/presentation/b18035723 is v3 and canonical.

figgy.title: Arabic section titles are not appearing as Right To Left in Universal Viewer

comments.body:
https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/pull/5750 updates manifests as per the implementation proposal in the previous comment. However, UV only implemented the rtl direction feature for the metadata info pane, not for the leftPanel "Contents" iiif-tree-component.

Code references:

- the TreeView in the leftpanel module uses TreeNode for the elements of the table of contents https://github.com/UniversalViewer/universalviewer/blob/86f2cd47598ed2b2cef6b30fd3dc706b0c8b9807/src/content-handlers/iiif/modules/uv-contentleftpanel-module/TreeView.ts
- The TreeNode itself is defined in manifesto: https://github.com/IIIF-Commons/manifesto/blob/6e355e34c38b64b9cf9c366d6ff60006db341968/src/TreeNode.ts
  - the label is set in the constructor, making it much more difficult to override the behavior here, to the extent that it's either not actually possible or really not a good idea.
- Here's some code showing how it works in the metadata info pane: https://github.com/UniversalViewer/universalviewer.github.io/blob/85dac1a4274f53659ba136c2bcd7ce1ab8c9d908/vendor/uv/lib/iiif-metadata-component.js#L375-L382
- language direction configuration referenced in the UV ticket: https://github.com/UniversalViewer/universalviewer/blob/67ada49f6d866a51ab173d7166f6ddf04fffb471/src/content-handlers/iiif/extensions/uv-mediaelement-extension/options/en-GB.json#L50

Note that @tpendragon also tried just putting html as the manifest value, but that resulted in an error.

The proposed path forward is (not necessarily in this order):
* Work on UV upstream to implement the required feature, possibly in collaboration with someone in the UV community.
* Migrate from webpacker to vite (https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/issues/5734)
* Update figgy to use the latest UV release, ensuring we carry over local customizations

However, this path forward is a bigger project than we had hoped and the work will need to undergo prioritization again.
I created https://github.com/UniversalViewer/universalviewer/issues/916

tiger-data-app.title: Refactor MediaFlux Client to utilize new Mediaflux::Http requests

comments.body: @carolyncole this looks great. I ran this branch locally and everything works except the part to display the files associated with a given project. The files are created with the "Add Test Files" (I see them in the MF Desktop) but they are not being loaded in the Project page. I'll take a closer look this afternoon on why that is.

@carolyncole I think the issue is in this method in the `MediaFluxClient` class. It should pass the action "get-name" for the names to come back in the response:

```
  def collection_query(collection_id, idx: 1, size: 10)
    query_request = Mediaflux::Http::QueryRequest.new(session_token: @session_id, collection: collection_id, size: size, idx: idx, action: "get-name")
    query_request.result
  end
```
@hectorcorrea give it a try now.  I added a test for that action, and put it in the MediafluxClient class
@carolyncole that did it.
